<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,603]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,328,151,177]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Gorgoniids branching mainly in multiple planes, lateral, partially dichotomous, or pinnatelike, often bushy. True neat dichotomy or pinnate branching rarely occur in this genus, but some species show close patterns: simple lateral branching and even dichotomous or pinnate sections, thus irregular branching, so these terms are used herein accordingly. Branch anastomosis absent. Axis horny, with a cross-chambered central core with a network of organic filaments frequently mineralized. (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1111,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="9.[151,255,835,859]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,811]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,197,811]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 2. Axis mineralization, SEM-micrograph of a longitudinal section of a terminal branch of Eugorgia multifida Verrill, 1868 (YPM 2257 b) after maceration in sodium hypochlorite; A, chambered core with mineralised filaments of CHAp; B, detail of CHAp microspheres coating organic filaments." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/188710/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Fig. 
<number box="[1096,1111,306,332]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A–B). Holdfast attached to hard substrates or extending on muddy sediments. Polyps fully retractile into the coenenchyme, in slightly raised to prominent mounds arranged in series of longitudinal rows, or evenly distributed on the branches. Coenenchymal sclerites of various 
<typeStatus box="[584,642,422,448]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
: spindle, disc-spindle, capstan, and the most dominant form that defines the genus is the characteristic double disc. Anthocodial sclerites rarely found, usually flat rods and platelets with lobed margins, forming a weak points-like arrangements at base of the polyp tentacles. Colour of colonies and sclerites variable: colourless, yellow, orange, red, violet, brownish, or combinations of these.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
